A lacking and mediocre successor to the original Sonic Runners. The most notable problem with this game is its utter lack of content. 9 characters and about 5 worlds that can be 100%ed in just a few days. If this was a free game, it'd at least be tolerable, but to pay money for a worse version of Runners was a tremendous disappointment. What this game needs is updates, adding new characters, new stages, and kind of incentive to play continuously, because as it stands, it's a quick cash-grab.

Several steps in the right direction in terms of game design and feeling 
like an ACTUAL game, this is a mobile game done right in my opinion. Takes 
away all the terrible roulette wheel RNG based unlocks of the original, 
which was what ruined the first game. However what it doesn't take is the 
look and feel of the original. The original Sonic Runners(R.I.P.) looked 
both fluid and lively, this one however doesn't even come close to what the 
original presented. I understand the decision to make it look more simple 
and less detailed so it runs on newer and older devices, but it still looks 
really rough. If the game had better models, animation, and an endless run 
mode it would be probably the best thing to grace the mobile gaming market 
in a long while. Tl;dr: Worth the $3, and hope to see more mobile games 
follow a format similar to this one.

Wonderfully fun with terrific graphics. You really get a sense of speed as you play through the game. The entire game depends on timing. If you can time your jumps perfectly, you can sail through the level in what feels like almost perfect harmony. It is a lot of fun if you can pull it off. The game is forgiving though and you can still complete levels even if you make a lot of mistakes. There are multiple characters you can pick from, although there are only four "types" of characters. So, you will have multiple models that do the same exact thing. You can also use different power ups to help you through a level and certain helpers. There is some variety here, but it would have been nice if there was even more! It does not detract from the game play, however. Highly recommended for those who like runners.

This game is very hit and miss. It's a simple and fast paced runner with multiple levels, each with their own objectives to fulfill, as well as a small amount of unlockables such as characters and buddies.  Some of my biggest problems were questionable level design in Lava Mountain and onwards (some examples being rockets with no visible warning, or level pieces in one character type's level clearly meant for another character type), as well as the arbitrary requirement of fulfilling the missions to progress through the game, and having looped levels where rings picked up previously don't respawn. Personally I'd like to just play the game level for level and move on after reaching the goal just like any other Sonic game.  Besides that, the graphics, while not as appealing as the original, look good, the music is ok, only using 5 tracks in total, all either from Sonic Runners or other official games, and the controls are responsive. I only failed some levels due to the problems mentioned above that artificially add difficulty. There also isn't much to bring you back after finishing the game, but its still an OK mini-revival of the original Sonic Runners (I still miss the original, though). An arcade-like endless mode is much needed for a game like this, as well as other fixes like reworked levels, but I doubt Gameloft is still supporting this game.

Arguable the best "made for mobile" Sonic game ever!  High praise, right?  Well considering this wasn't made by SEGA but licenced to a 3rd party developer the results are even more surprising. It's a very fun simple and addictive game, and shows again as with Sonic Mania that SEGA is finally listening to their huge army of supporters and letting fresh ideas thrive, while not forgetting what makes Sonic, Sonic.  Make no mistake, this game is every bit as good as Mario Run.  It costs money up front BUT you get the whole game which is very rare these days.    Good work guys! I love it!

Great work guys! A worthy tribute to the Sonic legacy without adverts or in-app rubbish. Solid, fun and fast gameplay befitting the character, coupled with all the sights and sounds of the original 90s game. Simple, easy to pick up gameplay with that classic "Just one more go!" feel. A must buy for all sonic fans and retro gamers alike.

Good: This is a great way to bring Sonic to mobile. It is like Mario Run, but it is done differently, it feels like Sonic and it feels good. The game also does well mixing mobile-game-style upgrades with old school Sonic power-ups. Bad: The levelling up seems like an unnecessary mechanic, though. I saw coins to level up, nothing seems to change. The button to level up is always green, even if I can't level up. The beautiful background while playing is a bit busy when I'm trying to focus on gameplay. I said to skip the tutorial, but I still was required to be forcefully guided through three levels before I could escape to a menu and backtrack to previous levels. Undecided: I am not far into the game, but I can tell that it will become difficult, quickly. Summary: Gameloft did a good thing. Buy the game.

The game also force closes fairly often (these issues persist even after tablet restart). Touch registers late a lot of times, and the automated fast scenes where the character is zooming through hoops and such are so laggy I can't even see what's happening. Outside of the actual levels, text is often too small to read easily, even on an 8" tablet. Too bad - I love the fact that this is a premium game, and it could have stayed on my device a long time. As it is, I'm uninstalling for a refund.

I do enjoy the game, but, when it comes to the original Sonic Runners, I think some of the features I would prefer. For example, the graphics on the the first one was more sleek and clean, while these, compared to the graphics of the one before aren't that hot. Secondly, the first game introduce a chance to just play free online with other opponents endlessly, unless you were hit withiut any rings or fell into a pit, while this one seems solely on a story mode which is fun, but I, along with others, sometimes don't wanna play story mode. Also, there is a high lacking in features, like the 14 "buddies" you have to chose from because the last one had over 50 of them and I would truly love for the other "buddies" were used. And, it would be very nice if they had special event only type of things, like how they introduced Gothic Amy. I just feel that its a great game, but if you add some of the features from the original Sonic Runners it would be even better. So, Gameloft, let Sonic stay with the Sega people, and you just stick with the Minions.

As someone who really loved the original Runners gameplay, I was very happy to see that the core of what made the game great is alive and well here. I actually prefer some of the changes here, like the inclusion of a mission based system over pure point scoring, the finite mission, the loop mission where rings collected on one lap stay missing on subsequent laps, and some of the spring and grind set pieces are a nice touch to show off the 3D engine, which feels smoother and better optimised on my galaxy note 2 than the original. That said, there are some things that are notably absent that I hope to see return in future updates, such as more buddies and characters, in-level power boxes (I've only seen the bonus stage box so far), invincibility music (which is sorely missed, especially as the invincibility is a lot less visually obvious), and more of the original Runners music in general. Also, having multiple bonus stages based on the various wisps would be nice, and a more significant reward for playing through them besides just more rings, such as some free to use power ups. On the whole, it's a good and well-deserved comeback that I hope to see grow over time.

Flight character gameplay is ridiculously bad. Far too floaty and imprecise controls with absolutely no indication of remaining flight time, which itself is far too short given how vague the controls are. Additionally, when hidden flight gauge does run out, the character then enters this state of simply not responding to any controls what so ever, which is extremely frustrating given the near endless number of spike traps and missiles that are unnecessarily crammed into the levels. These hazards also also have the annoying effect of taking away your controls without compensating with invincibility frames, resulting in an absolute mess of "gameplay" consisting of nothing but your character limping through the stage as they get battered like a pinball between endless hazards. The revival invincibility is also atrocius in how it also suffers from the lack of control problem infecting the game which causes you more often than not to become unstable again and return to the purgatory of hazard pinball that the player is punished with for missing jumps by literally milliseconds, which in itself will probably cause you to die again.
